# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Seabuster began as aerospace engineer Amarante No's proposal for a comprehensive refit of the popular Mekbuster conventional fighter. When the Draconis Combine showed no interest in the concept, she made her way to the Outworlds Alliance and secured financial backing from Praxton Fusion Products. Praxton bankrolled the entire project in exchange for exclusive rights to supply the 250-rated fusion engine to any future licensee of the design. Setting up shop in Praxton's warehouse facilities on the Alliance frontier, No began the lengthy manual refit process that would eventually produce one of the most specialized conventional fighters operating in the Periphery.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Seabuster's primary armament is an Improved Heavy Gauss Rifle, a weapon whose advanced recoil suppression system proved essential to the design's survival. The fifty-ton fighter's fusion engine provides a safe thrust of five, adequate for a heavy strike platform, and its flotation hull allows operation from any unimproved body of water of sufficient size--eliminating the need for costly airfield construction entirely. This amphibious capability gives the Seabuster a significant logistical advantage over STOL-equipped competitors in littoral and archipelago environments.</p><p>The Improved Heavy Gauss Rifle delivers devastating firepower on each pass, capable of crippling most armored targets with a single well-placed shot. However, the weapon's bulk limits the Seabuster to a single primary armament system, and the fighter lacks the secondary weapons that most pilots expect for self-defense during egress. Its armor protection is adequate for a conventional fighter but insufficient to survive sustained engagements with dedicated interceptors. The Seabuster is best employed in hit-and-run strikes from dispersed water bases, where its unique operating profile makes it difficult to suppress.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>In 3075, all six completed airframes were adapted with flotation hulls at the request of a prospective client on an unidentified water-rich world. This modification proved so popular it became a permanent fixture and gave the variant its new name. In its present configuration, the Seabuster fills an interesting niche for coastal and island defense forces that cannot afford dedicated airfield infrastructure.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Seabuster's development was nearly derailed when the first completed airframe, armed with a standard Heavy Gauss Rifle, suffered a catastrophic failure of the main wing spar during live-fire tests. A fault in the recoil suppression system tore the fighter apart, though the test pilot ejected safely. Completion of the second airframe was delayed five years while No attempted to resolve the recoil problem.</p><p>Ultimately, a deal with Defiance Industries saved the project. In exchange for undisclosed concessions, Defiance provided test samples of its Improved Heavy Gauss Rifle, whose advanced recoil suppression system reduced stress on the Mekbuster airframe to acceptable levels. After several successful trials, five additional fighters were assembled at the Praxton facility. No continued to seek prospective companies to produce the design at scale, and while her licensing agreements with Praxton Fusion Products and Defiance Industries made the Seabuster the most expensive Mekbuster variant to date, she remained confident that full-scale production would eventually follow.</p>
</history>

